"The European Court of Justice (ECJ) handed down its long-awaited Judgment in the IMS case at the end of April. 1 The key issue before the Court was to define the circumstances in which an owner of intellectual property (IP) rights might be ordered to grant a licence of those rights to a competitor – what is often termed a “compulsory licence”. The Court's ruling establishes two main points: first, competitors can obtain a compulsory licence of IP rights allowing them to compete on a market on which the owner of the IP rights is already present; and secondly, actual or would-be competitors can request a compulsory licence where the IP rights underlie a standard. These propositions are significant and the Judgment is sure to affect Microsoft's appeal to the European Court of First Instance against the recent Commission's decision. 2 It will also be of more general interest to businesses competing in IP-intensive industries – industries where competition law is increasingly being used as both a sword and a shield."
